    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">What is the cheapest gym membership in 2026?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Based on our data, Crunch Fitness, Youfit, Vasa Fitness, Chuze Fitness, and EōS Fitness all offer base plans starting at around $9.99 per month. Planet Fitness and Blink Fitness start at $10/month.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">Are gym initiation fees negotiable?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Often, yes. Many gyms run promotions where the initiation fee is waived or reduced to $1 (like Planet Fitness frequently does). If you sign up near the end of the month, salespeople are often more willing to waive these fees to hit their quotas.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">What does a premium gym like Equinox cost?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Premium gyms like Equinox average around $168 for base access and can go up to $230+ per month depending on location and access levels, often with a $100 initiation fee.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">Do any gyms offer month-to-month contracts without fees?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Yes, many gyms offer month-to-month contracts, but they may charge a higher monthly rate or require an initiation fee compared to signing an annual contract.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">Is CrossFit more expensive than a regular gym?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Yes, CrossFit is generally more expensive, averaging between $50 to $100+ per month depending on the box, but this includes coached group classes and specialized programming rather than just access to equipment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="methodology">
      <h2>Methodology</h2>
      <p>Data was collected in 2026 to reflect the most current pricing available. Sources included:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Official gym chain websites and localized pricing portals.</li>
        <li>Aggregated data from GymMembershipFees.com.</li>
        <li>User-reported actual prices from community forums like Reddit (r/fitness).</li>
